    {
      "description": "The contract specifies a late-payment rate of 2% per month, which annualizes to approximately 24.0%.",
      "document_position": 407,
      "excerpt": {
        "end_offset": 429,
        "section_id": "s1.3",
        "start_offset": 407,
        "text": "Late fee: 2% per month on past-due amounts."
      },
      "explanation": "Most US states cap consumer interest in the 18–24%/year range; commercial transactions allow higher contractual rates in many states but several (New York General Obligations Law §5-501, Tennessee, Arkansas pre-Constitutional-Amendment) hold the line tighter. A rate that would be standard in Texas or Delaware may be void in New York or California consumer contexts. Confirm against the controlling jurisdiction.",
      "id": "FIN-009-s1.3-407",
      "recommendation": "Confirm the rate is enforceable under the controlling state's usury rules. For consumer-facing contracts, consider capping at 18% annualized. For commercial contracts, document the parties' acknowledgement of the rate.",
